cannot measure the position

00:01:58.810 --> 00:02:07.420 align:middle line:84%
of a particle and its momentum
to arbitrarily good degree,

00:02:07.420 --> 00:02:10.900 align:middle line:84%
you're bound by if you
can measure the position

00:02:10.900 --> 00:02:13.420 align:middle line:84%
of a particle very well,
then your measurement

00:02:13.420 --> 00:02:18.650 align:middle line:84%
of the momentum is going to be
not so great and vice versa.

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:22.438 align:middle line:84%
And that's based
on an inequality,

00:02:22.438 --> 00:02:23.980 align:middle line:84%
and how do you prove
that inequality?

00:02:23.980 --> 00:02:25.430 align:middle line:90%
Integration by parts.

00:02:25.430 --> 00:02:28.730 align:middle line:84%
So integration by
parts is, in fact,

00:02:28.730 --> 00:02:32.710 align:middle line:84%
responsible for one of
