that the function f of x

00:03:45.750 --> 00:03:59.210 align:middle line:84%
can be expanded in terms
of simpler building blocks,

00:03:59.210 --> 00:04:00.630 align:middle line:90%
in terms of simpler functions.

00:04:00.630 --> 00:04:03.380 align:middle line:84%
So we haven't talked
about Taylor series.

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.620 align:middle line:84%
We will in just a
minute, or power series,

00:04:06.620 --> 00:04:08.120 align:middle line:84%
which you've come
into contact with,

00:04:08.120 --> 00:04:14.870 align:middle line:84%
which is a way of, if you like,
expanding a function in terms

00:04:14.870 --> 00:04:17.160 align:middle line:90%
of polynomials.

00:04:17.160 --> 00:04:21.050 align:middle line:90%
And now-- or monomials.

00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:29.730 align:middle line:84%
Now, Fourier
suggested that f of x

00:04:29.730 --> 00:04:34.260 align:middle line:84%
can be expanded as a
superposition of functions

00:04:34.260 --> 00:04:38.790 align:middle line:84%
which are 2 pi periodic and
kind of the most basic 2

00:04:38.790 --> 00:04:40.260 align:middle line:90%
pi periodic functions.

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:44.710 align:middle line:84%
Now, what is so special
about sine x and cosine x?

00:04:44.710 --> 00:04:47.850 align:middle line:84%
Well, this is a
little bit deeper,

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:50.310 align:middle line:84%
the fact that they satisfy
certain second order

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:51.960 align:middle line:90%
differential equation.

00:04:51.960 --> 00:04:56.670 align:middle line:84%
And they are all of the
solutions to the second order

00:04:56.670 --> 00:04:59.370 align:middle line:84%
differential equation
that are 2 pi periodic.

00:04:59.370 --> 00:05:01.880 align:middle line:90%


00:05:01.880 --> 00:05:04.550 align:middle line:84%
So you should think of these as
kind of being building blocks.

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:13.955 align:middle line:84%
Another way to think
of this is analogous to

00:05:13.955 --> 00:05:19.940 align:middle line:84%
for if you have a vector, so
now this is not a partition.

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:26.050 align:middle line:84%
This is a vector,
x1, x2, xn, then

00:05:26.050 --> 00:05:35.160 align:middle line:84%
you can expand this vector
as a sum of coefficients

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:42.347 align:middle line:84%
a sub n, a sub j,
j equals 1 to n.

00:05:42.347 --> 00:05:42.930 align:middle line:90%
You know what?

00:05:42.930 --> 00:05:47.880 align:middle line:84%
Let me make this M. Let's make
this N. Let's make this M,

00:05:47.880 --> 00:05:50.190 align:middle line:90%
so it looks a little--

00:05:50.190 --> 00:05:55.620 align:middle line:84%
a sub n, e sub,
where now, e sub n

00:05:55.620 --> 00:06:07.400 align:middle line:84%
this is the basis
vector given by 0 1 0

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:12.260 align:middle line:90%
where this is in the end spot.

00:06:12.260 --> 00:06:17.160 align:middle line:90%


00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:19.560 align:middle line:84%
So you can think
of this expansion

00:06:19.560 --> 00:06:21.840 align:middle line:84%
in terms of sines
and cosines as being

00:06:21.840 --> 00:06:29.820 align:middle line:84%
analogous to expanding a vector
in terms of basis elements.

00:06:29.820 --> 00:06:32.250 align:middle line:84%
Or you can think of
it as a different way

00:06:32.250 --> 00:06:37.980 align:middle line:84%
to expand a function other than
Taylor series or power series.

00:06:37.980 --> 00:06:44.790 align:middle line:84%
But these components
arose in a natural way

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:48.420 align:middle line:84%
if one were to study the
problem of heat transfer, which

00:06:48.420 --> 00:06:57.510 align:middle line:84%
is governed by the equation
dtu equals dx squared u.

00:06:57.510 --> 00:07:06.530 align:middle line:84%
And then, along with an initial
condition, that u of 0x,

00:07:06.530 --> 00:07:09.530 align:middle line:90%
so at time 0, equals f of x.

00:07:09.530 --> 00:07:13.176 align:middle line:90%


00:07:13.176 --> 00:07:23.600 align:middle line:84%
So now, just like for how we
expand a vector into basis

00:07:23.600 --> 00:07:28.970 align:middle line:84%
elements, there's a formula for
computing these coefficients.

00:07:28.970 --> 00:07:33.810 align:middle line:84%
So they should be a sub n
should be x sub n over here.

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:44.100 align:middle line:84%
But what's a different way of
obtaining these coefficients?

00:07:44.100 --> 00:07:46.650 align:middle line:90%


00:07:46.650 --> 00:07:50.200 align:middle line:90%
So this is a vector in RM.

00:07:50.200 --> 00:07:57.448 align:middle line:90%


00:07:57.448 --> 00:08:00.790 align:middle line:84%
And so, how do you obtain
the coefficients a sub n?

00:08:00.790 --> 00:08:05.680 align:middle line:84%
Well, if I take the inner
product of both sides,

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:13.450 align:middle line:84%
the dot product, say of e
x dot, let's say, e sub n

00:08:13.450 --> 00:08:15.640 align:middle line:90%
prime, let's say--

00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:18.700 align:middle line:90%
so I've used Mn, let's say l.

00:08:18.700 --> 00:08:25.540 align:middle line:84%
This is equal to the sum from n
equals 1 to the M of a sub n, e

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:29.020 align:middle line:90%
sub n dot e sub l.

00:08:29.020 --> 00:08:32.049 align:middle line:84%
Now, I wrote these basis vectors
this way, because that's kind

00:08:32.049 --> 00:08:34.720 align:middle line:90%
of a standard choice for RM.

00:08:34.720 --> 00:08:37.840 align:middle line:84%
And what makes them standard
is, they have unit length.

00:08:37.840 --> 00:08:41.570 align:middle line:84%
And they're orthogonal
to each other.

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:43.220 align:middle line:84%
So they form in
orthonormal basis.

00:08:43.220 --> 00:08:49.240 align:middle line:84%
So when I take the product
of e sub n with e sub l,

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:58.650 align:middle line:84%
I pick up what is usually
referred to as delta in l.

00:08:58.650 --> 00:09:08.340 align:middle line:84%
Where here, delta in l, this
is 1 if n equals l, and 0 if n

00:09:08.340 --> 00:09:09.390 align:middle line:90%
